{"type":"text","timestamp":1780929245290,"sessionID":"ses_1585c7ef3ffeE8bQgxmNtEsbEj","part":{"id":"prt_ea7a742f9001PpsN5Y2YIPnend","messageID":"msg_ea7a6710a00128qDUYKOtrNCtR","sessionID":"ses_1585c7ef3ffeE8bQgxmNtEsbEj","type":"text","text":"## Mechanism\nOpenLTM’s memory source of truth is the SQLite `memories` row: the module says it “replaces skills/learned/*.md with structured SQLite + FTS5,” the schema defines `content`, `dedup_key UNIQUE`, `confirm_count`, and `status` on `memories`, and the markdown dump is explicitly “auto-generated” and “do not edit directly” (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:1`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:35`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:45`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:709`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:727`). This depends on the row-write model.\n\n`learn()` scrubs content, derives a normalized `dedupKey`, looks up an existing row by `dedup_key`, then either updates that row by incrementing `confirm_count`, `last_confirmed_at`, and `confidence`, or inserts a new row and returns `created` with `confirm_count: 1` (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:304`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:307`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:314`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:323`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:347`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:352`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:414`). This is row-coupled reinforcement, not document editing.\n\nOpenLTM provenance and audit are per-row tables: `memory_provenance.memory_id` is a FK to `memories(id)`, while `memory_audit.memory_id` intentionally is not a FK so audit survives row deletion (`migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:6`, `migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:8`, `migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:1`, `migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:2`, `migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:6`). The DAO snapshots row fields from `memories` and writes before/after JSON audit rows (`packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:15`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:18`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:37`). This is mostly row-write audit machinery.\n\nOpenLTM’s cited `dedup.ts` is not a content hash; it lowercases, strips punctuation, collapses whitespace, trims, and truncates content to 200 chars (`packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:8`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:11`). A separate janitor also deduplicates row memories by embedding similarity and can merge rows by updating content, marking one row superseded, repointing relations, and boosting `confirm_count` (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:64`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:90`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:244`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:265`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:324`). This is row identity management.\n\n## Storage-fit teachings for system-spec-kit (doc-based)\n- **Claim** · Reinforcing duplicate facts by incrementing `confirm_count` does not survive the doc model; repeated authored-doc saves are no-ops or deliberate edits, not epistemic confirmations · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:317`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:323`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:347` · **Storage-fit** · ROW-COUPLED · **Maps-to** · none — row-coupled · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.94 · **Re-shaping needed (if DOC-ANALOG)** · n/a\n- **Claim** · Idempotency survives only as document/index freshness, not as fact reinforcement · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:5`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md:1053` · **Storage-fit** · DOC-ANALOG · **Maps-to** · index / MCP · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · LOW · **Confidence** · 0.89 · **Re-shaping needed (if DOC-ANALOG)** · use file path plus cryptographic content hash to skip unchanged re-indexing; never bump confidence or importance because a document was re-saved\n- **Claim** · Per-row provenance is redundant for canonical memory authorship because system-spec-kit routes saves into canonical docs and resumes from the continuity ladder · **Evidence** · `migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:6`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:27`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/README.md:66`, `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/README.md:97` · **Storage-fit** · ROW-COUPLED · **Maps-to** · none — row-coupled · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.84 · **Re-shaping needed (if DOC-ANALOG)** · n/a\n- **Claim** · Before/after JSON audit of memory rows is only useful if narrowed to non-doc operational DB mutations, not canonical memory content · **Evidence** · `migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:6`, `migrations/009_add_memory_audit.sql:13`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:15`, `packages/openltm-core/src/dao/provenanceAudit.ts:37` · **Storage-fit** · DOC-ANALOG · **Maps-to** · index / MCP · **Verdict** · ADAPT · **Risk** · MED · **Confidence** · 0.76 · **Re-shaping needed (if DOC-ANALOG)** · audit destructive or repair operations on derived indexes, while authored markdown plus git/continuity remains memory provenance\n- **Claim** · Heuristic or semantic row dedup/merge should not be ported because duplicate-looking text can be valid in different authored documents and ladder roles · **Evidence** · `packages/openltm-core/src/dedup.ts:5`, `packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:45`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:244`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:324` · **Storage-fit** · ROW-COUPLED · **Maps-to** · none — row-coupled · **Verdict** · REJECT · **Risk** · HIGH · **Confidence** · 0.92 · **Re-shaping needed (if DOC-ANALOG)** · n/a\n\n## Row-coupled findings (negative knowledge)\n- `created|reinforced` is negative knowledge: it treats duplicate row text as confirmation evidence, which authored docs do not imply (`packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:96`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:321`).\n- `confirm_count` as truth-strength is negative knowledge: it is a row counter, not a document-quality or decision-validity signal (`packages/openltm-core/src/schema.sql:48`, `packages/openltm-core/src/db.ts:324`).\n- Per-memory provenance rows are negative knowledge for canonical authored memory: source traceability belongs in the doc, continuity metadata, and git, not a shadow row table (`migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:1`, `migrations/008_add_memory_provenance.sql:8`).\n- Row merge/supersede dedup is negative knowledge: it mutates row identity, relations, tags, and counters instead of asking an author to reconcile documents (`packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:264`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:276`, `packages/openltm-core/src/janitor/dedup.ts:324`).\n\n## Open questions\nShould system-spec-kit keep a narrow operational audit for index repairs, retention sweeps, and MCP deletes that are not fully represented by git-visible doc edits?\n\nShould retrieval explainability prefer source document path, anchor, save timestamp, and git revision over row-derived signals such as `confirm_count`?","time":{"start":1780929217273,"end":1780929245280},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0c57ea9b08512cb4016a26d2c13d888191ad3abc211fc2f0da","phase":"final_answer"}}}}
